#!/bin/sh
# Ensure the commit produced by the preceding git-commit stage has tests.
#
# This command is intended to be the final stage of a pipeline.  It delegates
# the code/test assessment to the coding agent because deciding whether a
# change is adequately covered requires understanding the changed behaviour.

set -eu

repo_root=$(git rev-parse --show-toplevel 2>/dev/null) || {
    printf '%s\n' 'ensure-tests: not inside a Git work tree' >&2
    exit 1
}
cd "$repo_root"

# A pipeline starts every process at once.  Waiting for stdin to close means
# git-commit (the preceding stage) has finished creating the commit before the
# ensurer examines HEAD.  Do not pass that output to the agent.
if [ ! -t 0 ]; then
    cat >/dev/null
fi

if ! git rev-parse --verify HEAD^{commit} >/dev/null 2>&1; then
    printf '%s\n' 'ensure-tests: no commit exists to inspect' >&2
    exit 1
fi

prompt=$(cat <<'TASK'
Inspect the immediately preceding commit (HEAD) and ensure its JavaScript
changes are covered by both unit tests and feature/acceptance tests.  This is
a test-ensurer pass after another agent has made a commit.

First inspect the commit itself, including its parent diff (and handle a root
commit too), and identify every meaningful
JavaScript source change.  Do not infer coverage merely from the existence of
a test file: reason about the changed behaviour and verify that tests exercise
it.  Treat JavaScript source files such as *.js, *.mjs, and *.cjs as relevant;
do not treat test files, generated dependencies, or configuration-only changes
as application JavaScript changes.

For each relevant application change, require both:
* a focused unit test covering the underlying logic; and
* a feature/acceptance test covering the externally observable behaviour.

Use the existing project test conventions and tools.  If either kind of
coverage is missing or inadequate, create or improve the smallest appropriate
tests, including feature steps/support code when necessary.  Do not rewrite
valid production code just to make the tests pass, and do not make unrelated
changes.  Keep any pre-existing user worktree changes out of the commit.
Run the relevant unit and feature test commands (and lint when practical).

If the commit has no relevant application JavaScript changes, or already has
adequate unit and feature coverage, leave HEAD and the worktree unchanged.
If you added or changed tests for this commit, stage only those test changes
(and any strictly necessary test configuration/support changes), amend HEAD,
and retain the original commit message while adding this exact sentence to
its body: "Amended by ensurer agent."  The amended commit must therefore
explicitly tell readers that the ensurer agent amended it.  Never create a
second follow-up commit, amend an earlier commit, or commit unrelated files.
TASK
)

# The agent is intentionally detached from the pipeline's stdin.  The barrier
# above provides synchronization without allowing the agent to consume the
# preceding command's output.
exec mswea codex:gpt-5.6-luna@high --yolo --exit-immediately -t "$prompt" </dev/null
